<br>
the group known as &quot;Quakers&quot; is more formally known as<br>
&quot;Society of Friends.&quot; <br>
The nickname &quot;quakers&quot; came from their particular style of<br>
prayer at the time, where the pray-er moved back and<br>
forth, or 'quaked'.   Another group was given the nickname<br>
&quot;shaking quakers&quot; (the &quot;Shakers&quot;.) <br>
<br>
I heard of non-Christian quakers a few months back.<br>
Does not compute for me, but it makes sense to them, so<br>
there you go.<br>
<br>
I took an online quiz once, that supposedly shows what<br>
religion your beliefs are closest to.<br>
The closest Christian group I got was Quaker.<br>
<br>
Then again, I had a 100% correlation, I think, with<br>
&quot;conservative Jew&quot;, so that tells you how accurate the<br>
results were. (I think Muslim was a close second for me.)<br>
<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
I've never understood the &quot;Christians aren't allowed to have<br>
fun&quot; people.  I'm not too sure how many people would be<br>
interested in a God that had a vested interest in denying you<br>
all forms of fun.<br>
<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Here's some of my own personal history:<br>
(as much as I'm willing to share with the group)<br>
<br>
I was raised Roman Catholic, in a Roman Catholic family.<br>
At age 12, I was nearly killed.  Reviewing the incident <br>
convinced me that God existed (too many improbable things<br>
stacked up to insure I'd make a full recovery), but it left me<br>
with many questions that I was certain my upbringing left<br>
me ill-equipped for.  My own education had led me to <br>
believe that if Catholicism did not have the answers I was<br>
looking for, then NO Christian would. So, I spent the next<br>
few years essentially as a monotheist, looking for answers.<br>
Eventually, God sent a search party for me.  (When the<br>
time was right.) <br>
