<br>
<br>
That's basically what the little pamphlet in the back of the pew said, and it makes some sense.  You want people to be taking communion because they are true believers, not because they think theyr'e supposed to or whatever.  But I also saw something on it about the belief that the bread and wine/grape juice actually BECOMES the body and blood...and that kinda creeped me out...I mean, I'm alright with the symbolism, and how it becomes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>for us</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the body and blood of Jesus, but...actually physically turning into flesh and blood?  That's kinda creepy.  Is that just me misunderstanding the pamphlet, or is it something I just didn't think Lutherans did??  I was confused.  I dunno.  O_O;;  *shrug* <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jebleez>Jebleez</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sir Jeb,<br>Sword Wielding<br>Tone & Rhythm Man</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#B87333>(9/4/03 12:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://killeenroos.com/2/battle2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Denominations: Your history?</span><hr size=1> If you read that in a pamphlet, then you were most likely in a Catholic church, not a Lutheran church.<br>
Lutherans don't believe that the body and blood are physically there, but that they are present in the wine and bread. The view that you are talking about is called transubstantiation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You want people to be taking communion because they are true believers, not because they think theyr'e supposed to or whatever.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To be more precise, we want to make sure people who are partaking aren't flying blind into the situation. It's not right to be taking communion when you don't understand what is happening. And as other denominations believe different things about it, we prefer to have a closed communion. <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Politics is supposed to be the second oldest profession. I have come to realize that it bears a very close resemblance to the first.&quot; -Unknown<br>
